In [13]:
def plot_cloud(text):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(width = 500, height = 500, background_color='#40E0D0', 
                          colormap="ocean",  random_state=10).generate(text)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
    plt.imshow(wordcloud) 
    plt.axis("off")

Model 1: KNN¶

In [16]:
# split the data into train and test sets
# 0 for ham and 1 for spam
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(feature_vectors, [0] * len(smsham) + 
            [1] * len(smsspam), random_state = student_no, test_size=0.2) 


#define knn classification variable
knn = KNeighborsClassifier() 

# Define the dictionary of hyperparameters (number of neighbours and p) for gridsearch evaluation
hyperparameters = { 

        'n_neighbors': [1, 3, 5, 9, 11], 

        'p': [1, 2] 

    } 

# use grid search to determine the best parameters
knn = GridSearchCV(knn, hyperparameters, scoring='accuracy') 

#train the KNN classifier using hyperparameter tuning. 
knn.fit(X_train, y_train) 

print('Best p:', knn.best_estimator_.get_params()['p']) 

print('Best n_neighbors:', knn.best_estimator_.get_params()['n_neighbors']) 

Best p: 2
Best n_neighbors: 1

In [18]:
#get accuracy score
results.loc['knn','accuracy']=accuracy_score(y_test,y_predicted) 

#get balanced accuracy
results.loc['knn','balanced_accuracy']=balanced_accuracy_score(y_test,y_predicted) 

#get the training time in seconds
results.loc['knn','training_time']=knn.cv_results_['mean_fit_time'].mean() 

#get the prediction time in seconds per sms
results.loc['knn','prediction_time']=knn.cv_results_['mean_score_time'].mean()/len(y_test) 

print('the accuracy score is: ',results.loc['knn','accuracy'])
print('the balanced accuracy score is: ',results.loc['knn','balanced_accuracy']) 


print('the training time in seconds is: ',results.loc['knn','training_time']) 
print('the prediction time in seconds (per sms) is: ',results.loc['knn','prediction_time'])

Model 1 v2 - Use SMOTE to rebalance data and run again¶

In [19]:
#Generate synthetic samples of the class “spam” and thereby balance the training set.
X_train_smote, y_train_smote =SMOTE().fit_resample(X_train, y_train) 

#check that 50% of samples in training set are spam

sampleratio = y_train_smote.count(1)/len(y_train_smote)
if sampleratio == .5:
    print('the data is balanced with a ratio of: ', sampleratio)
else: print('the samples are not balanced with a ratio of: ', sampleratio)

print('Best p:', knn.best_estimator_.get_params()['p']) 

print('Best n_neighbors:', knn.best_estimator_.get_params()['n_neighbors']) 

the data is balanced with a ratio of:  0.5
Best p: 2
Best n_neighbors: 1

Model 2 Decision Tree¶

In [22]:
#run the decision tree classifier
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier() 

#define the dictionary of hyperparameters 
#(minimum samples for a node split, minimum samples for a leaf and maximum depth of tree) 
#to be evaluated using grid search.

hyperparameters = { 

    'min_samples_split': [2,3,5], 

    'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 50, 100], 

    'max_depth': [2, 3, 5, 10, 20] 

} 

# grid search to determine the best parameters according to the metric "accuracy". 
#Run the code below to add the grid search technique to the classifier `dt`. 
dt = GridSearchCV(dt, hyperparameters, scoring='accuracy') 

#train decision tree classifier via hyperparamter tuning
dt.fit(X_train, y_train) 

print('Best max_depth:', dt.best_estimator_.get_params()['max_depth']) 

print('Best min_samples_leaf:', dt.best_estimator_.get_params()['min_samples_leaf']) 

print('Best criterion:', dt.best_estimator_.get_params()['criterion']) 

Best max_depth: 20
Best min_samples_leaf: 5
Best criterion: gini
